, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1190–1264":"about 1190–1264","1190–1264":"1190–1264","1209–1265":"1209–1265","1228–1299":"1228–1299","1257–Male":"1257–Deceased","1259–Male":"1259–Deceased","1174–1251":"1174–1251","1174–Female":"1174–Deceased","1190":"1190","1264":"1264","1251":"1251","1174":"1174","1228":"1228","abt 1257":"about 1257","abt 1259":"about 1259","1215":"1215","1259":"1259","1202":"1202","1224":"1224","1257":"1257","1299":"1299","1265":"1265","1209":"1209","Abt 1190":"about 1190","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Kings Winterborne, Dorset, Eng.":"Winterborne Stickland, Dorset, England","Dewlish, Dorset, England":"Dewlish, Dorset, England","North Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","St Martin's, Weymouth, Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"St Martin's, Weymouth, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Normandy, France":"Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":25,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":34,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":69,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Gouvis was born about 1190, in Dewlish, Dorset, England, his father, Robert de Gouvis II, was 17 and his mother, Mrs Robert de Gouvis II, was 18. He had at least 3 sons with Countess Beatrice de Mandeville - Countess of Lincoln, Co Heiress. He died in 1264, in St Martin's, Weymouth, Dorset, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 75."},"et":{"Abt 1190–1264":